Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
To refound the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the common project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, was the third to put a draft for a new Constitution to the vote.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to the official results referring to 80% of the vote.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28 %, 7% of the suffrage was null and 0.7 % were blank.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it should obtain half the plus one suffrage.
On Sunday, two polls carried out at the exit of the electoral centres and a count from a non-governmental organization had announced a broad victory to the "yes", estimated from 63% to 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on Sunday night on Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The " Constitution triumphed in a crushing manner " , I had assured the Ecuadorians who head the Guayaquil government, 280 kilometres southwest of Quito.
So, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will take place in full calm, according to the observer mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text of 444 points consolidating the " new socialism " defended by the President.
The draft Constitution implies an increase in State power over the economy, reserving the " development planning " of a country that lives essentially through the extraction of oil by foreign companies and foreign currencies that send their emigrants.
With Correa, elected in 2006, the draft also gives strengthened powers to the head of State, which may carry out up to two consecutive mandates of four years each and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa already announced that he would use this power and would seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services which the President began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50 per cent of the population lives under the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as the starting point for American drug operations.
The 19 people kidnapped have been released in Chad
An Egyptian command launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by the Egyptian special forces in Chad.
They all looked good at their arrival at 3:30 p.m. on board a special plane to the military base of Al Maza, adjacent to Cairo's international airport.
They were immediately transported by helicopters to Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, to be subjected to medical tests, so they were unable to speak to the press.
"They find themselves healthy" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, said Egyptian tourism minister Zoheir Garana at the airport.
On 19 September these hostages fell into possession of 35 unknown kidnappers while enjoying a safari in allterrestrials in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and since then moved from one zulu to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Egyptian travel agency, in charge of the Safari organization.
An Egyptian security officer indicated that 30 members of the special forces, transported on board two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
"An exchange of shots took place, and they killed half the kidnappers, the others fled," said this manager who kept the anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces were sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commands.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of the Italian special forces.
"It must be acknowledged that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men from the secret services, the special forces," he said without going into detail.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
On the eve of the Sudanese army he claimed to have intercepted during a patrol an all-terrestrial on which the kidnappers were found, of whom he killed six, including the Chadian chief and arrested two.
He also stated that they were related to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan-United Nations Liberation Movement (SLA-U), a statement that was immediately denied by this group.
Letters - Silent majority of culture
A debate on the financing of culture takes place in the headlines and occupies the current electoral campaign.
Better that way.
But a sector of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the miserable amounts granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or to the national historical places that starve?
What politician will dare to remind the federal government that he neglects his monuments and heritage buildings?
Why do we not have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage as in Canada and Quebec?
Did you know that the French government spend three and a half million euros to restore only the castle of Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In the United States, it is written in its Constitution that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage has to be protected by all citizens, all elected and all government departments, and all this, in concert.
In Quebec, in the Federation of history societies of Quebec, at least 40,000 Benevolous people regrouped in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned with searching history, preserving with little money piles of private files and preserving archaeological remains.
These are often the guardian dogs of our heritage, who protest with energy and despair when promoters and leaders throw their bulldozers against our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
For when, is it a monument to history and heritage?
The Governments of the Netherlands nationalise part of the Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands - being the first in Europe - will help the Belgian-Fortis bank with nationalization, which is in trouble because of the U.S. mortgage crisis: the three countries will support a total of EUR 11.2 billion to this financial and insurance institution which also has business in Hungary.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands have held higher-level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the Head of Economic Competition of the European Commission.
Fortis Bank is the first to suffer from the euro area crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been taking place in several waves more than a year ago, so decisions taken with regard to the Bank can in some ways be regarded as precedents.
According to the decision taken in the early morning of Sunday, the three States will purchase approximately half (49 percent) of the property owned by the Bank in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell a part of its business, including all the activities - mainly insurance - purchased last year of ABN Amró Dutch.
The actions of the Fortis began a strong decline last week and by the second half of the week there were important signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree to point out that with their 85,000 employees this Bank is too large to allow it to break down.
The company's actions only on Friday decreased by 12 percent, being that the lowest point in the last 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares decreased by more than two thirds.
By observing the current prices of shares, the total value of the group’s capital on the market is about 14 billion euros, but according to the company’s executives this is not real.
The Bank’s management imposed the sudden fall of the actions of the Fortis to the insecurity of the US market in relation to the approval of the US package plan of $700 billion.
On Monday the actions already showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed new bank director general.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has given a specific offer.
The Belgian government had already ensured that investors had nothing to worry about, they would not lose their money.
Among Bank customers there was no panic so far, they did not invade bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also purchased leasing companies.
