The European Union doubles its trade with India
Since the European Union and India are reciprocally trading partners, this subject in addition to the other global problems dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-India summit will also be held today to deal primarily with nuclear energy cooperation.
While the European Union recognizes that India is a great democratic developing power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue has not been addressed at the ninth summit launched yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, EU President-in-Office, José Manuel Barroso, President of the Commission and Javier Solana, Senior Representative for Foreign Policy, received Manmohan Singh, Prime Minister of India, with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, i.e. to increase to over EUR 100 billion, their trade.
Given that the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not an excessively ambitious objective.
Thus, they legally harmonized the twenty-six bilateral civil aviation conventions existing with India, so also air transport can fly in the future.
India wants to sign the free trade treaty with the Union until the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up negotiations.
The objective is balance, because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only in the ninth place among the Union's trading partners.
The summit paid its attention to global affairs.
Both parties condemned the Afghan and Pakistani situation and terrorism - all forms of terrorism - and urged the convening of a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha trade liberalization round was also hastened, although both parties have great responsibility for its failure.
The EU confirmed that it will adhere to its energy and climate programme, that is, by 2020 it wants to reduce polluting emissions by at least twenty percent.
India also agrees with this, as at the next year's climate conference a global agreement should be reached and by 2050 the production of greenhouse gases should be reduced by 50 per cent.
They also wished to impede the increase in food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today the head of government of India will travel to the French capital, where - in a bilateral meeting - will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris trusts that French companies will receive charges worth EUR 20 billion to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency information the agreement would be for a period of 15 years.
